In article <+Uupu*yu6@aargh.adsp.sub.org>,
	marc@aargh.incubus.sub.org writes:
>Oh,  by the way:  I don't know about Ida, but I'd never trust an executable
>which  is  approved  by a few bytes of email header only.  Executing it may
>render  Idas  computer  useless, or insecure.  Imagine one sends her a fake
>executable  installing  a  keyboard  capture  hack,  which  tells her (when
>executed) that the message got damaged and could not be decrypted anymore.

Agreed - but the idea is still fairly useful if you want to encrypt several
executables for your own use. There are still gaping security holes, though -
a malicious attacker might replace the executable with a file which asks
for the password, stores it elsewhere, then reports a file-corruption.

